@bolkedebruin just to circle back -- it appears to be because sqlite has no native date type and sometimes the conversion doesn't work (why that's happening in this case and not others I don't know). http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/dialects/sqlite.html#date-and-time-types

It also seems that sometimes sqlite stores dates as strings and sometimes as integers, and perhaps we're just getting caught up in a mismatch here. https://www.sqlite.org/datatype3.html#date_and_time_datatype

In any case, many of the fixes I found are essentially the same one implemented here (for example http://stackoverflow.com/questions/16228195/comparing-dates-with-sqlalchemy-sqlite), so I feel comfortable that the PR is properly addressing the issue.

@r39132 in that case we should do something like this:

If a TI is running, server will send the log text along with the pointer (no of bytes) upto which log has been read. In next call, UI will pass that pointer in ajax call and server will send only the new logs after that pointer along with the new pointer. 

On UI rather than replacing the dom content, it'll just append to it. This process will continue until the TI finishes. On full page refresh UI will send no pointer and server will respond to full logs.
